issue.title: requestTimeout and long running uploads

labels.name: http
labels.description: Issues or PRs related to the http subsystem.

issue.body:
### Version

v18.14.0

### Platform

Linux prometheus 6.1.9-200.fc37.x86_64 #1 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Thu Feb  2 00:21:48 UTC 2023 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux

### Subsystem

http

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Create an HTTP server with a big `requestTimeout` (a day in this example):

```js
require('node:http').createServer({
  requestTimeout: 24 * 60 * 60 * 1e3, // a day
}, (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.method, req.url);

  req.resume().on('end', () => {
    res.end('Ok');
  }).on('error', console.warn);
}
).listen(8080);
```

Do a long running request to it:
```console
$ curl -T /dev/urandom http://localhost:8080 -v
*   Trying 127.0.0.1:8080...
* Connected to localhost (127.0.0.1) port 8080 (#0)
> PUT /urandom HTTP/1.1
> Host: localhost:8080
> User-Agent: curl/7.85.0
> Accept: */*
> Transfer-Encoding: chunked
> Expect: 100-continue
> 
* Mark bundle as not supporting multiuse
< HTTP/1.1 100 Continue
* Mark bundle as not supporting multiuse
< HTTP/1.1 408 Request Timeout
< Connection: close
< 
* Send failure: Connection reset by peer
* Closing connection 0
curl: (55) Send failure: Connection reset by peer
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

It happens everytime, and I haven't been able to pinpoint the exact value at which it becomes problematic.

### What is the expected behavior?

It should interrupt the request after 24 hours.

### What do you see instead?

It interrupt the request after ~30 seconds.

### Additional information

I can work-around by disabling the timeout (`requestTimeout: 0`) completely but setting a value, even high, seemed preferable.

Any other suggestions on how to handle long running uploads?

issue.body: I'm new to Flutter/Dart and was trying to configure it to preserve trailing commas. This is nicely documented [here](https://github.com/dart-lang/dart_style/wiki/Configuration#preserve-trailing-commas) but I only found that after asking @DanTup in Discord. It's not discoverable from VSCode, Google search and coding agent didn't find it, and search [here](https://dart.dev/search?q=trailing) also didn't find it. This ticket is a feature request to add some hover info in `analysis_options.yaml` (and probably similarly for `pubspec.yaml` would be great) that has a link to the right docs page to make it possible to discover the available options. As an example of what I mean, here's what I see if I open a Python project `pyproject.toml` - a clickable link to the docs where all the options are listed. Would be great if we had that on hover over "formatter or "linter" in `analysis_options.yaml`.

comment.body:
> > I think that this issue is requesting a way to see what not-yet-included options could be added to the file.
>
> I did miss this bit.. I originally thought the request was just for hovering over the existing keys to know what they had ...

Yeah, I think this request is about making the functionality available through these files more discoverable. Having a CodeLens to get to the documentation would help, but we need to ask whether there's a better solution (that would obviate the need for a CodeLens) and/or whether there's some additional support that would work _with_ a CodeLens to make it even more discoverable.

That's part of what made me think about the lints. A link to the documentation about what lints are supported would be good, but would be inconsistent with documentation of the form "Here's a list of the options you can nest under this key." On the other hand, listing all the lints in a single hover is not practical.

> > How do we get information to display related to plugins?
>
> If you mean when you hover over a plugin name, is there a description and URL in the metadata for a plugin? (or can we infer them from the package name?).

Sorry, my question was very terse. I was thinking fairly broadly that we should have a goal to make it possible for plugins to have a first-class UX. Anything we can show in the hovers for our own lints plugin authors should be able to supply for their lints. That potentially covers a lot of things.

- If we were to have a CodeLens to open documentation about the analysis options file, then plugins ought to be able to provide a URL to open documentation about the plugin's options and we ought to have a CodeLens above the plugin name to open that page.
- If we display docs when the cursor hovers over a lint name, then plugins ought to be able to provide documentation to display for their own lints.
- If we display docs while hovering over keys, then plugins should be able to provide docs for any keys they introduce.
- And given that we support code completion in these files, plugins ought to be able to contribute enough information that we can build a `MapProducer` that allows us to complete their values.

I don't know what that API would look like or whether we have anything on our roadmap to add such support for the initial version, but we should keep it in mind when designing this feature.

There is no parallel backend API in skbase today, while sktime, skpro, and Hyperactive each carry their own backend selection and configuration using the pair backend and backend_params. 

**Describe the solution you'd like**

I propose to add a small skbase.parallel module that defines a common interface for parallel execution. Once skbase provides this shared primitive, downstream projects can remove duplicate code and depend on the central API. This is a rough sketch how those classes could look like:

```python
class LokyParallel:
    n_jobs: Optional[int] = None
    prefer: Optional[str] = None 
    require: Optional[str] = None 

class RayParallel:
    ray_remote_args: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None
    shutdown_ray: bool = True
    logger_name: str = "ray"
    mute_warnings: bool = False

class DaskParallel:
    scheduler: Optional[str] = None 
```

**Describe alternatives you've considered**

A nested dictionary with a single top level key was considered instead of a dataclass because it encodes the dependency in one parameter. This is harder to explain and invites deep untyped structures, which burden documentation and error messages.

CodSpeed is a **continuous benchmarking** platform that allows you to **track** and **compare** the **performance** of your codebase during development.

The core of the **performance measurement** is done directly within your **CI environment** through the **CodSpeed Action**. Allowing you to **stay the sole owner** of your data and to keep your **codebase private**.

Once the performance data is generated, **only the benchmark results** are sent to the CodSpeed servers to be **analyzed**.

Then, performance reports are **generated** and **published** directly **within your repository provider**.

If **you haven't any benchmarks yet**, we provide an **intuitive** benchmarking API that allows you to **create your first benchmarks** in a **few minutes**.
